This is a film about deceit. In fact, each of the three characters are double-crossing one of the others in one way or another. What do you get when the double-crossers are double-crossing each other? Triple-crossing? Then that's what it is.

The film is set in Korea during the Japanese occupation. Two women and a man are engaged in complicated shenanigans, involving gender, sexual preference, social class, nationality and even language. Each character is pretending, in order to deceive the others.

In each of the three parts, a new level of deceit is shown. Sometimes parts of the story are repeated from another angle, to show how things are slightly different from how you think they were. Confused? Don't bother to understand. It'll all become clear when you see the film.

Visually, this movie is absolutely great. Each scene, even if it lasts for only a few seconds, is beautiful. The lighting, the camera angles, the costumes, the scenery, the make-up - everything is picture perfect.

The flip side is that the visual perfection takes away much spontaneity. The film is extremely stylish, perhaps even a bit too much so. But the visual bravado is not empty. There's a lot going on at each moment, and the imagery is always in line with the story itself. Only the explicit lesbian sex scenes seem to go on longer than strictly necessary - but who am I to complain?
