No spoilers...

Oh my. I was a big fan of UK dramatisation, "The Fingersmith" so was a little worried about "Ahgassi" translating across the sea. I was primarily concerned with the issue of conservatism over there, especially in Korea where censorship can be quite harsh at times. I honestly did not expect the full-on, pretty much nothing left to the imagination rendition of a rather graphic novel. Bravo!

My worries were unfounded: not only was Park Chan-wook able to convey the imagery convincingly, the rather complex story-in-two-parts translated wonderfully. The timeline (30's occupied Korea) the utterly sumptuous settings of the Japanese/European style mansion amidst the almost desolate beauty of the countryside and finally, The strong, character driven story lines acted out by a first rate, suitably gorgeous cast.

As a Japanese speaker, I found the Japanese half of the movie to be blissfully well acted and the Japanese convincing enough, considering the Korean cast... However I was forced to rely on some sub-par subtitling for the Korean half having only sparing knowledge.

Finally, having the original novel and the UK screen version to compare against, If found that the story told here was as triumphant and thoroughly heart-warming ode to trust as was the original and so well adapted to the Korean 30's that it felt truly in place in the sumptuous sets and in the hands of the gorgeous cast.
